        <name>1.4.1.14 Simplifying algebraic fractions</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Leave the expression in its most simplified form&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol class="HELM_parts_inline"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;\(\displaystyle{{@a1@}}\)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;\(\displaystyle{{@a2@}}\)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;\(\displaystyle{{@a3@}}\)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;\(\displaystyle{{@a4@}}\)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When simplifying remember only common factors can be cancelled.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h4 class="HELM_solution"&gt;Solution&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;[[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;[[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;[[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]] [[feedback:prt4]]&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;We have that \((x+1)\) is a common factor between the numerator and the denominator of \(\displaystyle{{@a1@}}\) and so we have:
&lt;p&gt;\(\displaystyle{{@a1@}} = \displaystyle{{@ta1@}}\)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There are no more common factors between the numerator and denominator and so this is the final answer&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;If we first factorise the numerator and the denominator of \(\displaystyle{{@a2@}}\) we see that \((x+1)\) is again a common factor and so can be cancelled to give:
&lt;p&gt;\(\displaystyle{{@a2@}} = \displaystyle{{@ta2@}}\)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Here we can see that \({@ev(7-2*n3,simp)@}\) divides every term in the expression \(\displaystyle{{@a3@}}\) and so dividing the numerator and the denominator by \({@ev(7-2*n3,simp)@}\) gives us:
&lt;p&gt;\(\displaystyle{{@a3@}} = \displaystyle{{@ta3@}}\)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Just as before this cannot be simplified further&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;By factorising the numerator of \(\displaystyle{{@a4@}}\) we can see that the term \((x-{@ev(n4+2,simp)@})\) is a common factor between the numerator and the denominator and hence we have:
&lt;p&gt;\(\displaystyle{{@a4@}} = \displaystyle{{@ta4@}}\)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</generalfeedback>
